1. To detect which key was pressed and whether it was the alt, ctrl, or shift key, we can listen for the "keydown" event and use the "keyCode" property of the event object to check which key was pressed. We can also use the "altKey", "ctrlKey", and "shiftKey" properties of the event object to check whether the corresponding modifier key was pressed along with the regular key. Here's an example:

```
document.addEventListener("keydown", function(event) {
  console.log(event.keyCode); // log the ASCII code of the key pressed
  console.log(event.altKey); // log whether the alt key was pressed
  console.log(event.ctrlKey); // log whether the ctrl key was pressed
  console.log(event.shiftKey); // log whether the shift key was pressed
});
```

2. To prevent the context menu from being displayed when the user right-clicks, we can listen for the "contextmenu" event and use the "preventDefault()" method of the event object to prevent the browser's default context menu from appearing. Here's an example:

```
document.addEventListener("contextmenu", function(event) {
  event.preventDefault(); // prevent the context menu from appearing
});
```

3. To create a form with a custom "timeout" event that fires after 30 seconds of inactivity, we can use the "setInterval()" method to periodically check whether the user has entered any data in the form, and fire the "timeout" event if not. We can also use the "preventDefault()" method of the event object to stop the form submission if the user chooses to cancel it. Here's an example:

HTML:
```
<form id="myForm">
  <label for="name">Name:</label>
  <input type="text" id="name" name="name">
  <br>
  <label for="email">Email:</label>
  <input type="email" id="email" name="email">
  <br>
  <input type="submit" value="Submit">
</form>
```

JavaScript:
```
var myForm = document.getElementById("myForm");
var timeoutId;

function startTimer() {
  timeoutId = setInterval(function() {
    if (!myForm.name.value && !myForm.email.value) {
      myForm.dispatchEvent(new Event("timeout"));
      clearInterval(timeoutId);
    }
  }, 30000);
}

myForm.addEventListener("submit", function(event) {
  if (!confirm("Are you sure you want to submit the form?")) {
    event.preventDefault(); // stop the form submission
  }
});

myForm.addEventListener("timeout", function(event) {
  alert("You have not entered any data in the form for 30 seconds.");
});
```

This code listens for the "submit" event on the form and shows a confirmation message asking the user whether they want to proceed with the submission. If the user clicks "Cancel," the "preventDefault()" method is called to stop the form submission. It also listens for a custom "timeout" event and shows an alert message if 30 seconds have passed without the user entering any data in the form. The "startTimer()" function is called when the page loads to begin the timer.

